{{Use British English|date=February 2018}}
[[File:Roman remains in 39 Bridge Street, Chester (3).JPG|thumb|right|Part of the Roman remains in the cellar]]

'''39 Bridge Street''' is a building in [[Chester]], [[Cheshire]], England.  It is recorded in the [[National Heritage List for England]] as a designated Grade&nbsp;I [[Listed building#England and Wales|listed building]], its major archaeological feature being the remains of a [[Roman architecture|Roman]] [[hypocaust]] in its cellar.<ref name=images>{{NHLE |num= 1376085|desc= 39&nbsp;Bridge Street, Chester|accessdate= 6 April 2012}}</ref>

The building has four storeys, with a shop at street level and a portion of [[Chester Rows]] in the storey above.  The hypocaust in the cellar dates to the 2nd&nbsp;century during the Roman occupation of Chester.  In the late 13th&nbsp;or early 14th&nbsp;century a [[England in the Middle Ages|medieval]] [[undercroft]] was built adjacent to the hypocaust, with a house above.  In 1864 a new floor was inserted at street level and a shop front was added in the 20th&nbsp;century.  The ground floor is now used as a café.  The remains of the hypocaust were found during the reconstruction of the property in 1864.  They consist of 27&nbsp;square columns in a rectangular chamber which originally contained 32&nbsp;columns in eight rows of four.<ref name=images/>

